  "prompt": "How is the part of the throat behind the nose called? What function does it serve?",
  "response": "The part of the throat located behind the nose is called the **nasopharynx**. It is the uppermost region of the pharynx, which is the muscular tube connecting the nasal and oral cavities to the larynx (voice box) and esophagus.\n\n### Functions of the Nasopharynx:\n1. **Air Passage**: The nasopharynx serves as an airway for breathing, allowing air to pass from the nasal cavity to the lower parts of the respiratory system.\n2. **Eustachian Tube Connection**: It contains the openings of the **Eustachian tubes**, which connect the nasopharynx to the middle ear. These tubes help equalize air pressure on either side of the eardrum.\n3. **Immune Function**: The nasopharynx houses the **adenoids** (pharyngeal tonsils), which are part of the immune system and help trap pathogens like bacteria and viruses entering through the nose.\n4. **Sound Resonance**: It plays a role in modifying the quality of sound during speech by acting as a resonating chamber.\n\nThe nasopharynx is a crucial anatomical structure for both respiratory and auditory functions, as well as immune defense.",
